DDoS Attacks Detected (27)

Critical security threat requiring immediate attention

What is a DDoS Attack?

A Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) attack floods your network with malicious traffic to overwhelm servers and disrupt legitimate services. Common types include SYN floods (TCP connection exhaustion), UDP floods (bandwidth saturation), and ICMP floods (ping storms).

Recommended Actions for Junior Engineers

1. Identify & Block Source

Add firewall rule to block attacking IP ranges. Use: iptables -A INPUT -s [SOURCE_IP] -j DROP

2. Enable Rate Limiting

Configure rate limiting on affected ports to prevent connection exhaustion. Check SD-WAN QoS policies.

3. Verify Target Services

Confirm if targeted IPs host critical services. Prioritize protection for business-critical systems.

4. Escalate if Persistent

If attack continues, escalate to security team and consider enabling upstream DDoS protection.

Port Scans Detected (4)

Reconnaissance activity detected - potential precursor to attack

What is a Port Scan?

Port scanning is a technique attackers use to discover open services on your network. Horizontal scans probe many IPs for one port (finding all web servers). Vertical scans probe many ports on one IP (mapping all services on a target). Block scans combine both approaches for comprehensive reconnaissance.

Scan Type Scanner IP Target IP Ports Probed Intensity Risk Level
VERTICAL 10.11.2.207 15 LIGHT Low - Probing
VERTICAL 10.199.1.118 15 LIGHT Low - Probing
BLOCK 10.11.2.207 11 LIGHT Low - Probing
BLOCK 10.199.1.118 7 LIGHT Low - Probing

Recommended Actions for Junior Engineers

1. Investigate Scanner Source

Check if scanner IP is internal (compromised host?) or external (attacker). Run: whois [IP]

2. Review Scanned Ports

Identify which ports were probed. Common targets: 22 (SSH), 3389 (RDP), 445 (SMB), 3306 (MySQL).

3. Check Target Vulnerabilities

Verify target hosts have up-to-date patches. Disable unnecessary services on scanned ports.

4. Monitor for Follow-up

Port scans often precede attacks. Set alerts for connections from scanner IP to discovered open ports.

TLS Security Issues (5)

Encryption vulnerabilities that could expose sensitive data

Understanding TLS Security

TLS (Transport Layer Security) encrypts data in transit. Vulnerabilities include: Weak ciphers (RC4, DES, MD5) that can be cracked, Outdated protocols (SSLv2/3, TLS 1.0/1.1) with known exploits, and Certificate issues (expired, self-signed, wrong hostname). These allow attackers to intercept or decrypt traffic.

Server Issue Type Details Severity Risk

10.11.4.5 Weak Cipher Suite Weak cipher suite detected: TLS_RSA_WITH_AES_256_GCM_SHA384 HIGH Security degradation

Recommended Actions for Junior Engineers

1. Identify Affected Services

Determine what application runs on the affected server. Check with app owners before making changes.

2. Update TLS Configuration

Enforce TLS 1.2+ minimum. Disable weak ciphers (RC4, DES, 3DES, MD5). Use: ssl_protocols TLSv1.2 TLSv1.3;

3. Renew/Replace Certificates

For certificate issues, renew expired certs or replace self-signed with CA-signed certificates.

4. Test After Changes

Verify fix with: openssl s_client -connect [IP]:443 or use SSL Labs scanner.

DNS Anomalies Detected (43)

Unusual DNS activity that may indicate security issues or misconfigurations

Understanding DNS Anomalies

DNS anomalies can indicate various issues: NXDOMAIN storms (malware trying random domains), DGA patterns (algorithmically generated malicious domains), DNS tunneling (data exfiltration via DNS), Suspicious patterns (unusual subdomains or query types), and Private IP responses (possible DNS hijacking or split-horizon misconfiguration).

Recommended Actions for Junior Engineers

1. Check for DNS Hijacking

If private IPs returned for public domains, verify DNS server config. Could be split-horizon DNS or actual hijacking.

2. Investigate Suspicious Domains

Check suspicious domains on VirusTotal or similar. DGA-like patterns may indicate malware on client devices.

3. Block Malicious Domains

Add confirmed malicious domains to DNS firewall blocklist. Consider using threat intelligence feeds.

4. Identify Affected Clients

Find which internal hosts are making suspicious queries. Run malware scans on those devices.

What is a TCP Handshake?

Before two computers can exchange data over TCP, they must establish a connection using a three-way handshake. This ensures both sides are ready to communicate and agree on initial sequence numbers.

Step 1: SYN Step 2: SYN-ACK Step 3: ACK Connection Ready!

What are TCP Retransmissions?

What is Network Latency (RTT)?

Round-Trip Time (RTT) measures how long it takes for a packet to travel to a destination and back. High latency causes slow response times, affecting user experience and application performance.

<50ms = Excellent 50-150ms = Moderate >150ms = High
54.86.210.162:443 10.11.2.173:61245
High Avg: 540.8ms Max: 1279.0ms
Latency Level:
540.8ms

What This Means

High Latency: Users will experience noticeable delays. Real-time applications (VoIP, video) will be severely impacted. Interactive applications will feel sluggish.

Common Causes of High Latency

  • Geographic distance - Data traveling long distances (e.g., cross-continent)
  • Network congestion - Too much traffic on the network path
  • Routing inefficiency - Packets taking suboptimal paths
  • Hardware bottlenecks - Overloaded routers or switches
  • ISP issues - Problems with internet service provider

Troubleshooting Steps

  • Run traceroute to 10.11.2.173 to identify where delay occurs
  • Check for network congestion on intermediate links
  • Verify routing tables for optimal path selection
  • Review QoS policies to prioritize latency-sensitive traffic
  • Contact ISP if destination is external and latency is on their network

High Latency: Users will experience noticeable delays. Real-time applications (VoIP, video) will be severely impacted. Interactive applications will feel sluggish.

Common Causes of High Latency

  • Geographic distance - Data traveling long distances (e.g., cross-continent)
  • Network congestion - Too much traffic on the network path
  • Routing inefficiency - Packets taking suboptimal paths
  • Hardware bottlenecks - Overloaded routers or switches
  • ISP issues - Problems with internet service provider

Troubleshooting Steps

  • Run traceroute to 10.11.1.216 to identify where delay occurs
  • Check for network congestion on intermediate links
  • Verify routing tables for optimal path selection
  • Review QoS policies to prioritize latency-sensitive traffic
  • Contact ISP if destination is external and latency is on their network

Understanding Protocol Distribution

Protocol distribution shows how network bandwidth is divided among different protocols. TCP typically dominates (web, email, apps), while UDP handles real-time traffic (VoIP, video). Unusual protocols may indicate security concerns or misconfigured applications.

About This Protocol

UDP (User Datagram Protocol) is used for real-time applications where speed is more important than reliability. Common uses include VoIP, video streaming, DNS queries, and online gaming.

Security Considerations

  • Watch for UDP floods which could indicate DDoS attacks
  • Verify UDP traffic is from expected applications

Modern multiplexed HTTP connections for faster web performance

What is HTTP/2?

HTTP/2 is a major revision of HTTP that enables multiplexing (multiple requests over one connection), header compression, and server push. It significantly improves web performance compared to HTTP/1.1.

HTTP/2 Features in Use

  • Stream Multiplexing: Multiple requests/responses share this single TCP connection
  • Header Compression: HPACK algorithm reduces header overhead
  • Binary Protocol: More efficient than HTTP/1.1 text format
  • Flow Control: Per-stream and connection-level flow control

What is QUIC?

QUIC is a modern transport protocol that runs over UDP instead of TCP. It provides built-in encryption, faster connection establishment (0-RTT), and improved performance on lossy networks. QUIC is the foundation for HTTP/3.

Protocol Reference Guide

Protocol Analysis Guide

Understanding Network Protocols

TCP Handshakes

Normal Behavior: TCP uses a three-way handshake to establish connections:

  1. SYN: Client sends SYN packet to server
  2. SYN-ACK: Server responds with SYN-ACK
  3. ACK: Client sends final ACK to complete handshake

Abnormal Behavior: Failed handshakes occur when SYN packets receive no response (server down/firewalled) or receive RST (connection refused).

Wireshark Filters:

  • tcp.flags.syn == 1 and tcp.flags.ack == 0 - See SYN packets (connection attempts)
  • tcp.flags.syn == 1 and tcp.flags.ack == 1 - See SYN-ACK packets (server responses)
  • tcp.flags.reset == 1 - See RST packets (connection refused/aborted)
  • tcp.analysis.flags - See TCP analysis flags (retransmissions, out-of-order, etc.)
HTTP/HTTPS

Normal Behavior: HTTP requests receive 2xx (success) or 3xx (redirect) responses.

Abnormal Behavior: 4xx errors indicate client-side issues (404 Not Found, 403 Forbidden). 5xx errors indicate server-side failures (500 Internal Server Error, 503 Service Unavailable).

Wireshark Filters:

  • http.response.code >= 400 - See all HTTP errors
  • http.response.code >= 500 - See server errors only
  • http.request.method == "GET" - See GET requests
  • http.request.method == "POST" - See POST requests
  • ssl.handshake.type == 1 - See HTTPS ClientHello packets
DNS

Normal Behavior: DNS queries receive responses with answer records. Response time is typically under 100ms.

Abnormal Behavior: NXDOMAIN (domain doesn't exist), timeouts (no response), excessive queries to random domains (DGA malware), or queries to suspicious domains.

Wireshark Filters:

  • dns.flags.response == 0 - See DNS queries
  • dns.flags.response == 1 - See DNS responses
  • dns.flags.rcode == 3 - See NXDOMAIN responses
  • dns.time > 1 - See slow DNS responses (>1 second)
  • dns.qry.name contains "suspicious" - Search for specific domains
ARP

Normal Behavior: ARP requests receive a single response mapping an IP to a MAC address.

Abnormal Behavior: Multiple MAC addresses claiming the same IP (conflict), excessive ARP requests (scanning), or gratuitous ARP from unexpected sources (spoofing).

Wireshark Filters:

  • arp.opcode == 1 - See ARP requests (who-has)
  • arp.opcode == 2 - See ARP replies (is-at)
  • arp.duplicate-address-detected - See ARP conflicts
  • arp.src.proto_ipv4 == 192.168.1.1 - See ARP for specific IP

What are Network Tunnels?

Tunnels encapsulate traffic inside other protocols for security, privacy, or network optimization. Common types include IPsec (VPN encryption), GRE (routing flexibility), VXLAN (data center overlay), and MPLS (carrier networks).
